If the `ignore` starts with a '.', then special changes are made:
```javascript
Browserify.prototype.ignore = function (file, opts) {
    if (!opts) opts = {};
    var basedir = defined(opts.basedir, process.cwd());

    // Handle relative paths
    if (file[0] === '.') {
        this._ignore.push(path.resolve(basedir, file));
    }
    else {
        this._ignore.push(file);
    }
    return this;
};
```

But these are not then applied when using it as a filter.
E.g.:
`browserify('path/to/file.js').ignore('./test.js')` doesn't seem to work if `file.js` contains `require('./test.js')`

I have a work-around by simply adding a check that replicates the ignore's `resolve` transform.
```javascript
    mopts.resolve = function (id, parent, cb) {
      // Handle relative paths
        if (id[0] === '.') {
          if (self._ignore.indexOf(path.resolve(basedir, id)) >= 0) return cb(null, paths.empty, {});
        }
        if (self._ignore.indexOf(id) >= 0) return cb(null, paths.empty, {});
```

